# Spleen

> The spleen is the **largest lymphoid organ** (~150 g, 12 × 7 × 3 cm), lying in the left hypochondriac region under ribs 9–11. It filters blood, removes aged erythrocytes, and stores platelets and immune cells. Unlike lymph nodes, it filters **blood** (not lymph).

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Lymphatic System]]
- Related organs: [[Stomach]] (gastrosplenic ligament, gastric surface), [[Kidney]] (splenorenal ligament, renal surface), [[Diaphragm]] (diaphragmatic surface), [[Pancreas]] (tail relates to splenic hilum)
- Blood supply: **Splenic artery** (largest branch of [[Celiac Trunk]]); tortuous course along superior border of pancreas
- Venous drainage: **Splenic vein** → joins SMV → **[[Portal System]]** (hepatic portal vein)
- Lymphatics: Splenic nodes → [[Celiac Trunk]] nodes
- Peritoneum: Intraperitoneal; gastrosplenic ligament (short gastric + left gastro-omental vessels); splenorenal ligament (splenic artery/vein + tail of pancreas)

## 🔬 Structure

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Fibrous capsule | Sends trabeculae into parenchyma |
| **Red pulp** (~80%) | Splenic sinusoids + splenic cords (Billroth); **blood filtration**; removes old/abnormal RBCs |
| **White pulp** (~20%) | Periarterial lymphatic sheaths (PALS, T cells) + lymphoid follicles (B cells); **immune surveillance** |
| Marginal zone | Interface between red + white pulp; antigen trapping |

## ⚙️ Function
- **Blood filtration** — removes senescent RBCs (120-day lifespan), opsonised bacteria, platelets
- **Immune function** — largest secondary lymphoid organ; IgM production; opsonin (properdin, tuftsin)
- **Platelet reservoir** — stores ~30% of circulating platelets
- **Erythropoiesis** — in fetal life (up to week 28); extramedullary haemopoiesis in adults when needed
- **Iron recycling** — haemoglobin → bilirubin (sent to liver) + iron (recycled)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Splenomegaly** — causes: malaria, EBV (mononucleosis), portal HTN, haematological malignancies, storage diseases; soft and tender vs. hard and non-tender
- **Hypersplenism** — overactive spleen → pancytopaenia; Rx: splenectomy
- **Splenic rupture** — traumatic (left lower rib fracture); spontaneous (EBV); **haemoperitoneum; surgical emergency**
- **Post-splenectomy** — risk of OPSI (overwhelming post-splenectomy infection) — encapsulated organisms (*Streptococcus pneumoniae, H. influenzae, N. meningitidis*); vaccinate + penicillin prophylaxis
- **Splenic artery aneurysm** — most common visceral artery aneurysm; women; pregnancy risk

